Nov. 2015Timo 10 Comments After posting my experiment of using Framework7 with TypeScript and Angular I get quite some questions from people on how to properly use F7 with Angular, so I made a quick screencast:How to use Framework7 with AngularJSHere are the links from the video:Template Download on GithubLive demoScreencast source code downloadFramework7 docsMy Twitter Site How to scroll up by tapping status bar in Cordova/PhoneGap Mon, 05. Oct. 2015Timo 1 Comment Holy, moly! This issue has been chasing me for more than 3 years! Ive always been a passionate Cordova/PhoneGap developer, even if many people dont like it: I personally think its not a bad platform if you got experience and you know what youre doing.However, since apps built with Cordova/PhoneGap completely rely on webkit and html, scrolling usually feels a little slow which is the reason why many people use a trick: They blow up a div element to 100% width and height and use -webkit-overflow-scrolling:touch to get smooth momentum scrolling within the div.Now, this works pretty good but the tradeoff is that you loose the ability to easily scroll up in your app by simply tapping the status bar on the top of the screen in iOS. This is a big usability issue and needs to be fixed imho.So, heres the fix:First, you need to install this plugin: cordova-plugin-statusbar You can do so by simply opening terminal, cd to your project folder an run:cordova plugin add cordova-plugin-statusbarThis plugin will fire an event when status bar is tapped. Reading up on some disrupting startups out there and found one called TransferWise. The company is making it cheaper to transfer funds across countries by charging a flat fee for each transfer regardless of the amount being transfered. The company is close to raising a $1 billion dollar valuation through investors that include Sir Richard Branson and the venture capital firm Andreessen-Horowitz. On the site, there is a funny transcribed conversation between the founder and a bank representative into how exactly fees are determined when going through the bank to transfer money. TransferWise selling point is that it is transparent in its costs as well as cheaper. Describing itself as the Skype of currency exchange, the company takes the mid-market fee in the morning and freezes it for 24 hours. This is the exchange rate that will be used with people paying a fee (the same regardless of size of transfer) to use the service. I am still a little confused as to how the overall exchange works. A Business Insider article describes it as a payment matching scheme where money never actually leaves the country. "The company manages to offer its services so cheaply by matching up payments with those going the opposite direction using sophisticated software. So "your" money never actually leaves the country it's rerouted to someone who's being sent a similar amount by someone overseas. Your foreign recipient, meanwhile, receives their funds from someone trying to send money out of their own country." Clearly no two people will have the exact same amount being transfered across accounts, so how exactly will payments be matched? In any case, this is an interesting company attacking a notoriously slow-moving and, at times, inaccessible industry (in terms of transparency and consumer understanding) so I will be looking into how it will grow. 2. Unicorns in Silicon Valley: Still a blessing? Fortune magazine always has interesting content and this article is no different. I like Fortune because, unlike Harvard Business Review and The Economist, I don't get booted out after reading 5, or however-many articles I am allowed, per month. The article compares the mythical creature of the unicron to the rising presence of $1 billion companies. Once a rarity, there are now around 80 companies that have reached the status. Many forces are responsible for this occurrence and there are warnings against the opulence that is reminiscent of the late 90s dot-com bubble. A while back I read a piece by a survivor of the 90s crash, Marc Andreessen, and his belief that the regulation that resulted from the late 90s, primarily the Sarbanes-Oxley Act, has made IPOs more expensive for smaller businesses due to the amount of paperwork, legal costs and protocols that must be followed. Startups that would've gone public early on cannot afford to and so remain private and grow until they can bear the costs of making an initial public offering. Today's more financially conservative atmosphere (lower interest rates, for example) has lead more investors to seek higher rewards through startups. While the chance of finding another Google, Twitter or Facebook are slim, investors seem willing to take the risk. The Jobs Act of 2012 has made it possible for small businesses to take on a significant amount of investors and raise much more capital while remaining private. I can't decide if this article is foreshadowing a coming storm or merely a roadmap for other startups to follow. Key quote of the article: "U.S.-based companies raised more venture capital in the fourth quarter of 2014 than they did in any other quarter over the prior 13 years, according to the National Venture Capital Association." 3.
